What is a Semiconductor?
A semiconductor is a material with conductivity between conductor and insulator.


Example: Silicon (Si), Germanium (Ge)
It can conduct or block electricity depending on conditions.

Types of Semiconductors:
1. Intrinsic Semiconductor
Pure semiconductor (no impurities)
Low conductivity

2. Extrinsic Semiconductor (Doped)
Impurities are added to improve conductivity

Two types:
a) N-type Semiconductor
Extra electrons (negative charge carriers)
Majority carriers: Electrons

b) P-type Semiconductor
Missing electrons (called holes)
Majority carriers: Holes
P-N Junction
Formed by joining P-type and N-type materials
Creates a depletion region (no charge carriers)
Basis for diodes and transistors
